=========================================
LAMBDA EXPRESSIONS (C++11 onwards) – INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is a Lambda Expression?
------------------------------
- A lambda is an anonymous (unnamed) function.
- Introduced in C++11.
- Used to write inline, short functions without defining a separate function.
- Very commonly used with STL algorithms.

Syntax:
[capture](parameters) -> return_type {
    function_body
};

Example:
auto add = [](int a, int b) -> int {
    return a + b;
};

-----------------------------------------

2. Basic Example (Most Common)
------------------------------
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    auto greet = []() {
        cout << "Hello Lambda!" << endl;
    };

    greet();
}

-----------------------------------------

3. Lambda with Parameters
-------------------------
auto sum = [](int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
};

cout << sum(10, 20);

-----------------------------------------

4. Return Type (Optional in most cases)
--------------------------------------
- Compiler can deduce return type automatically.

auto mul = [](int a, int b) {
    return a * b;   // return type deduced as int
};

Explicit return type:
auto div = [](int a, int b) -> double {
    return (double)a / b;
};

-----------------------------------------

5. Capture List (VERY IMPORTANT)
--------------------------------
- Used to access outside variables inside lambda.

Types of capture:

(a) []  -> captures nothing
(b) [=]  -> capture all external variables by VALUE
(c) [&]  -> capture all external variables by REFERENCE
(d) [x]  -> capture specific variable by VALUE
(e) [&x] -> capture specific variable by REFERENCE
(f) [=, &x] -> default value capture, x by reference
(g) [&, x]  -> default reference capture, x by value

-----------------------------------------

Example:
int x = 10, y = 20;

auto f1 = [=]() { return x + y; };   // by value
auto f2 = [&]() { x++; };            // modifies original x

-----------------------------------------

6. Mutable Lambda
-----------------
- By default, captured-by-value variables are read-only inside lambda.
- mutable allows modification of copied values.

int x = 10;

auto f = [x]() mutable {
    x++;   // allowed (modifies copy)
    cout << x;
};

f();
cout << x;  // original x unchanged

-----------------------------------------

7. Lambda with STL (VERY IMPORTANT)
-----------------------------------
Example with for_each:

#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

vector<int> v = {1,2,3,4};

for_each(v.begin(), v.end(), [](int &x) {
    x = x * 2;
});

-----------------------------------------

8. Lambda in Sorting
--------------------
vector<int> v = {5, 2, 8, 1};

sort(v.begin(), v.end(), [](int a, int b) {
    return a < b;   // ascending order
});

-----------------------------------------

9. Generic Lambdas (C++14)
--------------------------
- Uses auto in parameters.

auto print = [](auto x) {
    cout << x << endl;
};

print(10);
print(3.14);
print("hello");

-----------------------------------------

10. Lambda with std::function
----------------------------
#include <functional>

std::function<int(int,int)> f = [](int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
};

-----------------------------------------

11. Common Interview Questions
-----------------------------
Q1: Why use lambda expressions?
- For short, inline functions
- Cleaner code with STL algorithms
- Avoids writing separate function

Q2: Difference between lambda and function?
- Lambda: anonymous, inline, can capture variables
- Function: named, no capture feature

Q3: What is capture list?
- Mechanism to access outer scope variables

Q4: Can lambda be stored?
- Yes, using auto or std::function

-----------------------------------------

12. Important Pitfalls
----------------------
- Dangling reference if capturing local variable by reference and lambda outlives scope
- Overusing [&] can lead to bugs
- Prefer explicit capture over [=] or [&] in production code

-----------------------------------------

13. Real-world Usage
--------------------
- STL algorithms (sort, for_each, count_if)
- Event handlers
- Callbacks
- Thread functions
- Functional programming style in C++

